                    <msContents>
                        <summary>A Safavid-era illustrated copy of the romance of <title>Khusraw and
                                Shirin</title>, one of the five poems of 
                            <title>Khamsah</title> (Quintet) by medieval Persian poet <persName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/2474895/" xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="standard"
                                key="person_2474895" change="#ids-cleanup">Niẓāmī Ganjavī (ca. 1140–1203)</persName>. While it bears a colophon
                            purportedly signed by Timurid-era scribe <persName key="person_f6371"
                                cert="medium" role="scr att">Mawlānā Aẓhār of Herat, d
                                1475-6</persName>, the illustrations within the volume appear likely
                            completed by commercial artists in <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                                from="1500" to="1600">sixteenth-century</date>
                            <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7002148"
                                >Shiraz</placeName>, then famed for their production of luxury
                            manuscripts for international clientele.</summary>
                        <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_6-item1">
                            <author key="person_2474895" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/2474895/">
                                <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="standard"
                                    key="person_2474895" change="#ids-cleanup">Niẓāmī Ganjavī, ca. 1140–1203</persName>; <lb/>
                                <persName xml:lang="fa">نظامى گنجوى</persName>
                            </author>
                            <editor cert="medium" role="scr att" key="person_f6371"><persName> Aẓhār
                                    of Herat, d 1475-6</persName></editor>
                            <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_20153">Khusraw va
                                Shīrīn</title>
                            <title xml:lang="fa">خسرو و شيرين</title>
                            <incipit xml:lang="ar" type="basmala"><locus from="1b" to="1b"> برگ ۱پ
                                    (folio 1b):</locus> خداوندا در توفیق بگشای * نظامی را ره تحقیق
                                بنمای.</incipit>
                            <explicit xml:lang="fa">
                                <locus from="66a" to="66a"> برگ ۶۶ر (folio 66a):</locus> روانش باد
                                جفت شادکامی * که گوید باد رحمت بر نظامی. </explicit>
                            <colophon xml:lang="fa">
                                <locus from="6a" to="66a"> برگ ۶۶ر (folio 66a):</locus> بنهایت رسید
                                کتابت کتاب خسرو و شیرین که آیت مبین خطاب مستبین خمسه‌‌ٔ متین مرشد
                                اهل یقین شیخ نظامیست در آوان ایام تفرقه وحوادث متفرقه که مستوعب
                                اوقات کتابت گشته بود لا جرم موجب تأخیر تمام در اتمام شد فی الرابع
                                عشرین من الشهر الفاخر ربیع الاخر سنه ۸۲۴ خدم بکتابتها العبد المفتقر
                                الی رحمة الله الغنی اظهر السلطانی. </colophon>
                            <colophon>Signed by <persName cert="medium" role="scr att"
                                    key="person_f6371">Aẓhār</persName>, with a date that may read
                                with <date cert="medium" when="1421-05-07">24 Rabī‘ II 824 AH (7 May
                                    1421 CE)</date> or <date cert="medium" when="1460-02-26">864 AH
                                    (26 Feb. 1460 CE)</date>.</colophon>
                            <note><persName key="person_122167091" role="cataloguer"
                                    change="#prov-markup">B. W. Robinson</persName> (<title>Ars
                                    Orientalis</title>, Vol. 11, p. 387 and <title>Persian
                                    Paintings</title>, p. 148) questions the authenticity of the
                                date, as the left and middle digits appear altered, and since the
                                illumination, illustrations, and binding all seem from the <date
                                    from="1501" to="1550">early sixteenth century</date>, rather
                                than the one prior. Furthermore, he observes how the date comports
                                with that calligrapher's known floruit and how the final inverse
                                triangular portion of the colophon may not be authentic since the
                                gold marginal ruling masks a join in the paper. More recently,
                                    <persName>Shiva Mihan</persName> (pp. 10, 17) argued in favour
                                of the signature's authenticity and interprets the date in the
                                colophon as <date cert="medium" when="1460-02-26">24 Rabī‘ II 864 AH
                                    (17 Feb. 1460 Julian)</date> instead. Recent multi-spectral
                                imaging conducted by the Rylands in <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                                    when="2022">2022</date> confirms the paper and ink comport with
                                the text, albeit remounted onto the attached margins and
                                gold-flecked when restored; however, the authenticity of the
                                signature and exact date await further comparison and
                                corroboration.</note><lb/>
                            <note>For another illustrated manuscript of this same work, see Rylands <ref
                                target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_26569"><idno>Persian
                                    MS 969-2</idno></ref>, in addition to complete copies of the
                                <title>Khamsah</title> .</note>
                            <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                        </msItem>
                    </msContents>
